# Ending Sexual Violence in the Military: A Comprehensive Analysis and Recommendations

## Abstract

Sexual violence in the military remains a pervasive and complex issue that undermines the safety, morale, and operational readiness of armed forces. Despite decades of legislative efforts, policy reforms, and awareness campaigns, sexual assault and harassment continue at alarming rates within the U.S. military. This report synthesizes extensive research, legislative developments, survivor testimonies, and expert analyses to provide an in-depth understanding of the problem and proposes concrete, actionable strategies to end sexual violence in the military. Emphasis is placed on cultural transformation, accountability mechanisms, judicial reforms, and leadership engagement as critical pillars for effective change.

---

## Introduction

Sexual violence in the military is a systemic problem with profound consequences for victims, military cohesion, and national security. Female service members are statistically more likely to be sexually assaulted by fellow service members than to be harmed by enemy combatants during deployment. The Department of Defense (DoD) has reported thousands of sexual assault cases annually, with low conviction rates and widespread underreporting due to fear of retaliation and lack of trust in the military justice system ([Council on Foreign Relations, 2021](https://www.cfr.org/podcast/sexual-assault-us-military)).

This report aims to analyze the root causes of sexual violence in the military, evaluate past and current reform efforts, and recommend comprehensive solutions grounded in evidence and survivor experiences.

---

## The Scope and Nature of Sexual Violence in the Military

### Prevalence and Reporting

- Approximately 7% of service members reported being victims of sexual assault in 2018, yet less than 4% of accused service members were convicted ([Scanlon, 2021](https://www.militarytimes.com/opinion/commentary/2021/12/13/military-justice-needs-sexual-assault-reform-survivor-says/)).
- Reports of sexual assault have increased steadily since 2006, with a 13% jump in 2018 and continued rises in subsequent years ([Associated Press, 2021](https://apnews.com/article/military-sexual-assault-prosecutions-congress-2021-12-08)).
- Underreporting remains a significant issue due to fear of retaliation, stigma, and lack of confidence in commanders and the military justice system.

### Cultural and Institutional Challenges

- A culture of tolerance toward sexual harassment and assault persists, with many service members perceiving such behavior as normative or unaddressed ([NPR, 2021](https://www.npr.org/2021/07/02/1012591478/a-commission-finds-quite-a-lot-of-tolerance-for-sexual-harassment-in-the-military)).
- Commanders wield disproportionate authority over prosecution decisions, creating conflicts of interest and undermining judicial independence ([Scanlon, 2021](https://www.militarytimes.com/opinion/commentary/2021/12/13/military-justice-needs-sexual-assault-reform-survivor-says/)).
- Victims often feel abandoned by leadership, with their trauma minimized to protect perpetrators' careers or the military's reputation.

---

## Critical Analysis of Past and Current Reform Efforts

### Legislative Actions

- The Furthering Accountability and Individual Rights within the Military Act of 2014 (FAIR Military Act) sought to eliminate bias and increase accountability but faced challenges in implementation ([Tsongas & Turner, 2014](https://www.csmonitor.com/Opinion/2014/0616/What-it-will-take-to-end-sexual-assault-in-the-military)).
- The 2022 National Defense Authorization Act (NDAA) included provisions to move sexual assault prosecution to independent prosecutors but retained commanders' convening authority, limiting judicial independence ([Scanlon, 2021](https://www.militarytimes.com/opinion/commentary/2021/12/13/military-justice-needs-sexual-assault-reform-survivor-says/)).
- Senator Kirsten Gillibrand and Representative Jackie Speier have championed historic reforms to remove prosecutorial decisions from commanders, though complete removal has yet to be achieved ([New York Times, 2021](https://www.nytimes.com/2021/12/07/us/politics/military-sexual-assault-reform.html)).

### Military Justice System Challenges

| Aspect                        | Current Status                              | Challenges                                      | Proposed Changes                              |
|-------------------------------|--------------------------------------------|------------------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------|
| **Prosecutorial Authority**    | Commanders decide prosecution referrals    | Conflict of interest, bias, lack of independence | Independent military prosecutors              |
| **Victim Support**             | Victim advocates under command structure   | Lack of independence, fear of retaliation       | Separation from command, independent reporting |
| **Accountability of Commanders** | Limited and inconsistent                    | Lack of consequences for failing to prevent or respond | Regular assessments tied to promotions        |
| **Training and Prevention**    | Mandatory but often perfunctory             | Quick, cheap, ineffective training               | Effective, frequent, culturally relevant training |

