## Recommendations for Ending Sexual Violence in the Military

Drawing from the comprehensive information and analyses, the following multi-faceted approach is recommended:

### 1. Judicial and Prosecutorial Reform

- **Remove prosecutorial decisions from commanders** to ensure impartiality and fairness in handling sexual assault cases. Independent military prosecutors should have exclusive authority to refer cases to courts-martial ([New York Times, 2021](https://www.nytimes.com/2021/12/07/us/politics/military-sexual-assault-reform.html)).
- **Establish independent victim advocacy and support services** outside the chain of command to provide unbiased assistance and protect victims from retaliation ([NPR, 2021](https://www.npr.org/2021/07/02/1012591478/a-commission-finds-quite-a-lot-of-tolerance-for-sexual-harassment-in-the-military)).

### 2. Leadership Accountability and Cultural Change

- **Hold commanders accountable for the safety climate under their command** by implementing regular, anonymous surveys assessing perceptions of safety, reporting confidence, and leadership intolerance of harassment ([Grenny, 2013](https://time.com/3809818/how-to-end-sexual-abuse-in-the-military/)).
- **Tie commanders’ fitness reports and promotions** to measurable outcomes in preventing sexual violence, not just completion of training activities ([Grenny, 2013](https://time.com/3809818/how-to-end-sexual-abuse-in-the-military/)).
- **Develop a prevention workforce** dedicated to educating, training, and supporting commanders and service members in creating a respectful environment ([NPR, 2021](https://www.npr.org/2021/07/02/1012591478/a-commission-finds-quite-a-lot-of-tolerance-for-sexual-harassment-in-the-military)).

### 3. Enhanced Training and Prevention Programs

- **Implement effective, evidence-based training** that goes beyond checkbox compliance, focusing on behavior change, bystander intervention, and cultural norms ([Grenny, 2013](https://time.com/3809818/how-to-end-sexual-abuse-in-the-military/)).
- **Measure training effectiveness** through feedback and behavioral indicators rather than mere participation rates.

### 4. Transparent Data Collection and Reporting

- **Disaggregate sexual assault data by unit and commander** to identify problem areas and hold specific leaders accountable ([Grenny, 2013](https://time.com/3809818/how-to-end-sexual-abuse-in-the-military/)).
- **Increase frequency of data collection** to align with commanders’ tenure and promotion cycles, enabling timely interventions.

### 5. Legislative Support and Oversight

- **Congress must continue oversight** to ensure effective implementation of reforms and resist dilution of critical provisions ([Tsongas & Turner, 2014](https://www.csmonitor.com/Opinion/2014/0616/What-it-will-take-to-end-sexual-assault-in-the-military)).
- **Pass comprehensive legislation** that fully removes prosecutorial authority from commanders and strengthens protections for victims ([Scanlon, 2021](https://www.militarytimes.com/opinion/commentary/2021/12/13/military-justice-needs-sexual-assault-reform-survivor-says/)).

---

## Conclusion

Ending sexual violence in the military requires a fundamental transformation of the military justice system, leadership accountability, and organizational culture. The current system's reliance on commanders for prosecutorial decisions creates conflicts of interest and undermines trust. Independent prosecution, victim advocacy, and transparent accountability mechanisms are essential. Moreover, commanders must be held responsible for fostering safe environments, with their career progression tied to measurable outcomes in preventing sexual assault.

Effective training, frequent data collection, and legislative support are critical to sustaining progress. Without these comprehensive reforms, sexual violence will continue to erode the integrity and effectiveness of the armed forces.

